description:
Although Yuji Itadori looks like your average teenager, his immense physical strength is something to behold! Every sports club wants him to join, but Itadori would rather hang out with the school outcasts in the Occult Research Club. One day, the club manages to get their hands on a sealed cursed object. Little do they know the terror they’ll unleash when they break the seal…

(Source: Viz Media)

Notes:
- Ranked 1st in Japan's Bookstore Employees Top Manga of 2018.
- Nominated for the 25th Annual Tezuka Osamu Cultural Prize in 2021.
- Nominated for the 65th Shogakukan Manga Award in the Shounen Category in 2019.
- Chapter count includes extra chapter.

[Twitter](https://twitter.com/tiffyshindo) Fédoua Lamodière (formerly Fédoua Thalal) is a French manga translator. She studied Japanese at INALCO from 1998 to 2003, and started translating working as a professional translator in 2001 with Pocket Monsters: PiPiPi★Adventure at Glénat editions. She also works for Pika, Ki-oon, Kaze and Taifu comics. She translated some famous works, such as Dragon Ball, Seven Deadly Sins, Witch Hat Atelier, Jujutsu Kaisen...
Her favourite manga are Dragon Ball, Attack on Titan and Hunter x Hunter.

node.description:
[Twitter](https://twitter.com/Yozudami)

Mizuki Yoda graduated from the Tokyo Designer Gakuin Manga Department. At the age of 19, they received the Honorable Mention and Grand Treasure Award in the 91st Jump Treasure Newcomer Manga Award (January 2015) for the work "Jigoku no Sata mo Ryuu Shidai". The judge for the award was [Takeshi Obata](https://anilist.co/staff/96888/Takeshi-Obata). It was published in Jump Next #3 (Shueisha) in 2015, marking her debut.
Former assistant of [Yuukou Osada](https://anilist.co/staff/98848/Yuukou-Osada), [Koyoharu Gotouge](https://anilist.co/staff/119973/Koyoharu-Gotouge) and [Gege Akutami](https://anilist.co/staff/125415/Gege-Akutami).

[Twitter](https://twitter.com/uszksr) Scouted by an editor from Shueisha and author Tatsuya Matsuki for her Samon the Summoner fan art, she moved from Kansai to Tokyo in order to start her career. She partnered up with Matsuki to publish the one-shot Welcome to the Asagaya Art Academy's Film Program, which became the basis for the serialization of ACT-AGE.
